1. Introduction

Authentication and authorization are common topics in backend development.

Many developers confuse:

Basic Auth
JWT
OAuth 2.0

They solve different problems.

Basic Auth = username/password based access
JWT = token-based authentication
OAuth 2.0 = delegated authorization framework
2. Basic Auth
What is Basic Auth?

Basic Authentication is an HTTP authentication method where the client sends username and password with every request.

How It Works

Client sends:

Authorization: Basic base64(username:password)

Example:

Authorization: Basic YWRtaW46MTIzNDU2

(Base64 of admin:123456)

Request Example
GET /api/users
Authorization: Basic YWRtaW46MTIzNDU2
Server Side

Server decodes Base64:

admin:123456

Then checks database.

Advantages
Very simple
Easy to implement
No token handling
Good for internal systems
Disadvantages
Password sent every request
Base64 is encoding, not encryption
Must use HTTPS
No expiry
No granular permissions
Best Use Cases
Internal admin tools
Testing APIs
Small trusted systems
3. JWT Authentication
What is JWT?

JWT = JSON Web Token

A signed token issued after login.

Instead of sending password every request, client sends token.

JWT Structure
header.payload.signature

Example:

eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJ1c2VySWQiOjF9.signature
Login Flow
Step 1

User logs in:

POST /login
{
  "email": "user@test.com",
  "password": "123456"
}
Step 2

Server validates credentials.

Step 3

Server returns token:

{
  "token": "jwt_token_here"
}
Step 4

Client sends token:

Authorization: Bearer jwt_token_here
Server Verification

Server checks:

Signature
Expiry
Claims
Example Payload
{
  "userId": 10,
  "role": "admin",
  "exp": 1714300000
}
Advantages
Stateless authentication
No session storage required
Good for APIs
Expiry supported
Works well with mobile/SPAs
Disadvantages
Hard to revoke immediately
Token theft risk if stored badly
Payload readable (not encrypted by default)
Best Use Cases
REST APIs
Mobile apps
React / Angular frontends
Microservices
4. OAuth 2.0
What is OAuth 2.0?

OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework that lets users grant apps limited access without sharing passwords.

Example

Instead of giving your password to a third-party app:

Bad:
Give Gmail password to App

Use OAuth:

Good:
Login with Google
Approve access
App gets token
Main Roles
Resource Owner = User
Client = App
Authorization Server = Login provider
Resource Server = API
Common Flow (Authorization Code Flow)
Step 1

User clicks:

Login with Google
Step 2

Redirect user to provider:

GET /authorize?
client_id=abc
redirect_uri=https://app.com/callback
response_type=code
scope=email profile
Step 3

User logs in with provider.

Step 4

Provider asks consent:

Allow access to profile/email?
Step 5

Redirect back:

https://app.com/callback?code=xyz123
Step 6

Backend exchanges code:

POST /token
grant_type=authorization_code
code=xyz123
client_id=abc
client_secret=secret
Step 7

Provider returns:

{
  "access_token": "abc123",
  "refresh_token": "xyz789",
  "expires_in": 3600
}
Step 8

App uses token:

Authorization: Bearer access_token
Advantages
User password not shared with app
Fine-grained permissions (scopes)
Revocable access
Token expiry
Best for third-party login
Disadvantages
More complex than JWT/basic auth
Multiple redirects
Token lifecycle management required
Best Use Cases
Login with Google
Login with GitHub
Microsoft API access
Enterprise SSO
Third-party integrations
